The integration of Retrieval-\nAugmented Generation (RAG) Large Language Models (LLMs) and multiple AI agents\ninto Human Resources (HR) technology holds the potential to revolutionise the\nHR landscape, bringing us closer to a future where AI can significantly\naugment or even replace traditional HR knowledge worker roles. By leveraging\nadvanced AI capabilities in a decentralised peer-to-peer (P2P) environment,\naligned with the emergent Web3 paradigm, HR technology can achieve\nunprecedented levels of efficiency, flexibility, and scalability. RAG LLMs\ncombine the generative capabilities of large language models with retrieval\nmechanisms that draw from extensive databases to provide accurate,\ncontextually relevant responses. This makes them ideal for handling the\ncomplex tasks often managed by HR professional knowledge workers. When\nintegrated with multiple AI agents, each specialised in different HR\nfunctions, these systems can provide comprehensive support across various HR\ndomains. Enhanced Efficiency and Accuracy AI agents powered by RAG LLMs can\nhandle tasks such as succession planning, recruitment, onboarding, performance\nevaluations, employee engagement and others, with greater accuracy and speed\nthan their HR counterparts. They can process vast amounts of data, identify\npatterns, and make informed decisions without the biases and limitations\ninherent in human cognition. RAG LLMs take us a step closer (we are not there\nyet) to Artificial General Intelligence (AGI), the Holy Grail of AI made\nfamous in science fiction movies, which seeks to mimic human behaviour and\ndecision-making. AGI aims to understand, learn, and apply knowledge across a\nwide range of tasks, just as a human would. By integrating RAG LLMs into HR\nsystems, we begin to approximate the holistic, adaptive problem-solving\ncapabilities that characterise AGI. These models can understand context, draw\nfrom extensive datasets, and provide mimicked, human-like responses, edging\ncloser to the comprehensive intelligence and versatility of AGI. The\ndecentralised P2P environment is a hallmark of Web3, promoting a shift from\ncentralised to distributed systems. This aligns perfectly with the\narchitecture of multi-agent systems in HR, where Machine-to-Machine (M2M)\ncommunication facilitates seamless interaction between various AI agents.\nBenefits of Decentralisation 1\\. Resilience and Redundancy: Decentralised\nsystems are inherently more resilient to failures as there is no single point\nof failure. This ensures continuous HR operations even if individual nodes or\nagents experience issues. 2\\. Scalability: Adding new agents or scaling\nexisting ones in a P2P network is straightforward, allowing HR systems to grow\norganically with the organisation. 3\\. Security and Privacy: Decentralised\nsystems offer enhanced security and privacy, crucial for handling sensitive HR\ndata. Distributed Ledger Technology (DLT) ensures data integrity and\ntransparency. Integrating P2P and M2M systems in HR technology brings the\nbenefits of edge computing and connects seamlessly with sensor devices and\nInternet of Things (IoT) technology. This connection at source enables real-\ntime data collection and processing, facilitating immediate decision-making\nand operational adjustments. For example, sensors in workplace environments\ncan monitor employee health and safety, feeding data directly into HR systems\nto prompt timely interventions. Additionally, P2P and M2M lay a perfect\nplatform for microgrid energy management combining employee data with\nmicrogrid managed systems to forecast load and consumption levels. The future\nof HR technology lies in custom-developed component products with embedded AI\ncode, something the current generation of HR software products cannot do. This\nnew era of HR solutions offers unparalleled flexibility, allowing\norganisations to adapt to changing business functions and processes as\ntechnology evolves. Customisation and Flexibility 1\\. Modular AI Components:\nAI code can be embedded as modular components within HR systems, enabling easy\nupdates and replacements as needed. This modularity ensures that the HR\ntechnology stack remains agile and responsive to new demands and innovations.\n2\\. Adaptability: As business processes and requirements change, AI components\ncan be seamlessly integrated or swapped out, maintaining alignment with the\norganisation's strategic goals and technological advancements. Current legacy\nHR systems are not designed to accommodate embedded AI without significant\nmodifications. Integrating AI into these systems typically requires complex\nAPI connectors, which can become cumbersome and costly to maintain, especially\nas business processes evolve. Limitations of Legacy Systems 1\\. Inflexibility:\nLegacy systems are often rigid, with fixed workflows that do not easily adapt\nto new technologies or changing business needs. 2\\. Complex Integration:\nEmbedding AI into legacy systems requires extensive custom development,\ncreating potential liabilities if business processes change or the technology\nbecomes obsolete. 3\\. High Maintenance Costs: Maintaining these integrations\ncan be expensive and resource-intensive, detracting from the overall\nefficiency gains promised by AI. Traditional HRIS (Human Resource Information\nSystem) methodologies for selecting and implementing HR systems are based on\nstatic requirements and long-term stability. However, the integration of AI\nagents necessitates a dramatic shift in these methodologies. New Selection and\nImplementation Strategies 1\\. Dynamic Requirements Gathering: Instead of\nstatic requirements, organisations will need to focus on dynamic and evolving\nneeds, ensuring that AI capabilities can be scaled and adapted over time. 2\\.\nAgile Implementation: Agile methodologies will become more prevalent,\nemphasizing iterative development, rapid prototyping, and continuous\nimprovement. 3\\. AI-First Approach: AI agents will be integral to the HR\ntechnology solution from the outset, not as add-ons but as core components\ndriving efficiency and innovation. DLT is set to transform HR technology\nsolutions fundamentally. Custom-built solutions on a DLT platform will become\nthe architecture of choice for companies aiming to enhance productivity and\nreduce the cost of technology ownership. Advantages of DLT in HR 1\\. Employee\nData Ownership and Portability: DLT provides the platform for the secure, and\nemployee approved, transfer of data between employers. 2\\. Enhanced Data\nIntegrity: DLT ensures that all HR data is immutable and transparent, reducing\nthe risk of data tampering and enhancing trust. 3\\. Decentralised\nApplications: HR applications built on DLT can operate in a decentralised\nmanner, reducing reliance on centralised servers and increasing resilience.\n4\\. Cost Reduction: By eliminating intermediaries and reducing the need for\nextensive infrastructure, DLT can lower the overall cost of ownership for HR\ntechnology solutions. Integrating decentralised HR technology with AI enables\nseamless communication with satellites and mesh networks, opening up\nopportunities for remote communities. For example, in Australia, satellite\ndata communication can provide remote communities with access to advanced HR\nsystems and AI-driven industry solutions, fostering new industries and skills\ndevelopment locally. The choice between human resources and augmented\nresources (AR) for business lines will necessitate a close examination of how\nboth entities draw upon the same business knowledge uploaded to LLMs. ARs, or\nAI agents, offer several advantages: 1\\. Cost Efficiency: ARs do not draw\nsalaries, providing a cost-effective solution compared to traditional HR. 2\\.\nAvailability: ARs are available 24/7, offering continuity and immediate\nresponse times, unlike human workers who require breaks and consideration\ntime. 3\\. Quality and Reliability: Business lines will need to compare the\nquality, accuracy, and reliability of advice from ARs versus HR before making\nbusiness partner decisions. To effectively utilise AI in HR, professionals\nneed to understand how LLMs work. LLMs learn from data by being trained on\nvast datasets, allowing them to recognise patterns and generate appropriate\nresponses based on this training. HR professionals must learn to collect\nrelevant data and annotate it to make it searchable, which assists AI in\nmaking the right conclusions. This involves a basic understanding of software\nstructure to determine where embedded code should reside within the HR system.\nUnless HR professionals understand AI, it will definitely replace them.\nHowever, if they know how it works, they can leverage AI to deliver superior\nservices to executives and line managers. Understanding the mechanisms behind\nAI allows HR professionals to utilise AI as a tool for enhancing decision-\nmaking, improving efficiency, and delivering more accurate and timely\nresponses. When making strategic decisions about adopting AI, HR leaders face\na critical choice between custom-built AI platforms and subscription models\nfrom large generative AI providers. Subscription models often require paid\nsubscriptions for each user across the business, leading to significant costs.\nMoreover, using such services means uploading sensitive company data to\nexternal servers, where it may be used to train the provider's model, posing\nrisks to data privacy. These subscription-based solutions also typically\ncannot be embedded in custom built HR applications without complex and fragile\nAPI connections, limiting integration capabilities. In contrast, custom-built\nAI platforms offer greater control and flexibility. They protect data privacy\nby keeping data within the company’s secure environment and can be tailored to\nmeet specific business needs. By opting for a custom-built solution, HR can\nensure a more reliable, integrated, and secure AI system that aligns closely\nwith organisational goals and requirements. Additionally, local deployment and\nprivate AI models provide a valuable asset of company knowledge, preserving\noperational and process information that would otherwise depend on key staff\nretention, especially during company acquisitions. In other words, an\nimportant factor in determining the value of a company could be assessed by\nthe quality and volume of their AI model data. The integration of RAG LLMs and\nmultiple AI agents within a decentralised P2P environment represents a\nsignificant leap forward in HR technology. These innovations promise to\nenhance efficiency, adaptability, and security, paving the way for a future\nwhere AI can augment or replace traditional HR knowledge worker roles. As the\nindustry shifts towards more flexible and dynamic HR technology solutions, the\nrole of AI agents and DLT will become increasingly central, transforming how\norganisations manage their human capital and achieve strategic objectives.\nThis paradigm shift will drive productivity improvements and reduce the cost\nof technology ownership, heralding a new era of HR technology aligned with the\nfuture direction of Web3 and beyond. About the Author John Macy has been\nworking with colleagues in the USA for the last five years on Web3,\nDistributed Ledger Technology, Decentralised HR technology and Artificial\nIntelligence as the HR software industry approaches a new era with a new\nfoundation platform. He will be sharing more information about material in\nthis article at the AHRI Queensland State Conference on the 13th June 2024.\nJohn.macy@cet-hr.com Workday Product Lead As usual John, your insight is\nimpressively laid out and easy to digest. This vision of AI makes a lot of\nsense. Early language models and information\nretrieval systems laid the foundation for prompt engineering. In 2015, the\nintroduction of attention mechanisms revolutionised language understanding,\nleading to advancements in controllability and context-awareness. Significant\ncontributions were made in 2018 and 2019 , with a focus on fine-tuning\nstrategies, control codes, and template-based generation. During this period,\nbreakthroughs in reinforcement learning techniques addressed challenges such\nas exposure bias and biases in generated text. In 2020 and 2021, contextual\nprompting and transfer learning improved prompt engineering. In 2022 and 2023,\nnew techniques like unsupervised pre-training and reward shaping appeared. For\nreaders already familiar with the landscape and technology, I’ll begin at\nnumber 10 and work my way back to number one. Web-Navigating AI Agents:\nRedefining Online Interactions and Shaping the Future of Autonomous\nExploration. Agentic exploration refers to the capacity of AI agents to\nautonomously navigate and interact with the digital world, particularly on the\nweb. Web-navigating AI agents are revolutionising online interactions by\nautomating complex tasks such as information retrieval, data analysis, and\neven decision-making processes. These agents can browse websites, extract\nrelevant data, and execute actions based on predefined objectives,\ntransforming how users engage with online content. By reshaping the way we\ninteract with the web, these AI agents are paving the way for more\npersonalized, efficient, and intelligent online experiences. As they continue\nto evolve, web-navigating AI agents are poised to significantly impact the\nfuture of autonomous exploration, expanding the boundaries of what AI can\nachieve in the digital realm. As agents grow in capability, they are also\nexpanding into navigating by leveraging the image / visual capabilities of\nLanguage Models. Firstly, language models with vision capabilities\nsignificantly enhance AI agents by incorporating an additional modality,\nenabling them to process and understand visual information alongside text.\nI’ve often wondered about the most effective use-cases for multi-modal models,\nis applying them in agent applications that require visual input is a prime\nexample. Secondly, recent developments such as Apple’s Ferrit-UI, AppAgent v2\nand the WebVoyager/LangChain implementation showcase how GUI elements can be\nmapped and defined using named bounding boxes, further advancing the\nintegration of vision in agent-driven tasks. An AI Agent is a software program\ndesigned to autonomously perform tasks or make decisions based on available\ntools. As illustrated below, these agents rely on one or more Large Language\nModels or Foundation Models to break down complex tasks into manageable sub-\ntasks. These sub-tasks are organised into a sequence of actions that the agent\ncan execute. The agent also has access to a set of defined tools, each with a\ndescription to guide when and how to use them in sequence, addressing\nchallenges and reaching a final conclusion. Agentic applications refer to\nsoftware systems that utilise autonomous AI agents to perform tasks, make\ndecisions, and interact with their environment with minimal human\nintervention. According to recent studies these applications leverage large\nlanguage models (LLMs) to drive agent behaviours, enabling them to navigate\ncomplex tasks across various domains, including web navigation, data analysis,\nand task automation. By integrating LLMs with other modalities like vision and\nreinforcement learning, agentic applications can dynamically adapt to changing\ninputs and goals, enhancing their problem-solving capabilities. The study\nhighlights how these agents can be evaluated for effectiveness in different\nscenarios, pushing the boundaries of what autonomous systems can achieve. As\nagentic applications evolve, they hold the potential to revolutionise\nindustries by automating intricate workflows and enabling new forms of\nintelligent interaction. The underlying principle which enables RAG is In-\nContext Learning (ICL). In-context learning refers to a large language model’s\nability to adapt and generate relevant responses based on examples or\ninformation provided within the prompt itself, without requiring updates to\nthe model’s parameters. By including a few examples of the desired behaviour\nor context within the prompt, the model can infer patterns and apply them to\nnew, similar tasks. This approach leverages the model’s internal understanding\nto perform tasks like classification, translation, or text generation based\nsolely on the context given in the prompt. In-context learning is particularly\nuseful for tasks where direct training on specific data isn’t feasible or\nwhere flexibility is required. Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) combines\ninformation retrieval and generativemodels. By injecting the prompt with\nrelevant and contextual supporting information, the LLM can generate telling\nand contextually accurate responses to user input. Below is a complete\nworkflow of how a RAG solution can be implemented. By making use of a vector\nstore and semantic search, relevant and semantically accurate data can be\nretrieved. In machine learning, a pipeline is an end-to-end construct that\norchestrates the flow of events and data. It is initiated by a trigger, and\nbased on specific events and parameters, it follows a sequence of steps to\nproduce an output. Similarly, in the context of prompt engineering, a prompt\npipeline is often initiated by a user request. This request is directed to a\nspecific prompt template. Prompt pipelines can be viewed as an intelligent\nextension of prompt templates. They enhance the predefined templates by\npopulating variables or placeholders (a process known as prompt injection)\nwith user queries and relevant information from a knowledge store. Below is an\nexample from our GALE framework, on how a pipeline can be built in a no-code\nfashion. Prompt Chaining, also referred to as Large Language Model (LLM)\nChaining, is the notion of creating a chain consisting of a series of model\ncalls. This series of calls follow on each other with the output of one node\nin the chain serving as the input of the following. Each chain node is\nintended to target small and well scoped sub-tasks, hence one or more LLMs is\nused to address multiple sequenced sub-components of a task. In essence prompt\nchaining leverages a key principle in prompt engineering, known as chain of\nthought prompting. The principle of Chain of Thought prompting is not only\nused in chaining, but also in Agents and Prompt Engineering. Chain of thought\nprompting is the notion of decomposing a complex task into refined smaller\ntasks, building up to the final answer. The next step is to develop a library\nof prompt templates that can be combined at runtime to create more advanced\nprompts. While prompt composition adds a level of flexibility and\nprogrammability, it also introduces significant complexity. A contextual\nprompt can be constructed by combining different templates, each with\nplaceholders for variable injection. This approach allows for parts of a\nprompt to be reused efficiently. A contextual prompt is composed or\nconstituted, with the different elements of the prompts having placeholders as\ntemplates. A step up from static prompts is prompt templating. In this\napproach, a static prompt is transformed into a template by replacing key\nvalues with placeholders. These placeholders are then dynamically filled with\napplication values or variables at runtime. Some refer to templating as entity\ninjection or prompt injection. In the example template example below you can\nsee the placeholders of${EXAMPlES:question}, ${EXAMPlES:answer} and\n${QUESTIONS:question} and these placeholders are replaced with values at\nruntime. Generation is a core functionality of large language models (LLMs)\nthat can be effectively utilised, with prompt engineering serving as the\nmethod through which data is presented, thereby influencing how the LLM\nprocesses and responds to it. Text Generation Is A Meta Capability Of Large\nLanguage Models & Prompt Engineering Is Key To Unlocking It. You cannot talk\ndirectly to a Generative Model, it is not a chatbot. You cannot explicitly\nrequest a generative model to do something. But rather you need a vision of\nwhat you want to achieve and mimic the initiation of that vision. The process\nof mimicking is referred to as prompt design, prompt engineering or casting.\nPrompts can employ zero-shot, one-shot, or few-shot learning approaches. The\ngenerative capabilities of LLMs are significantly enhanced when using one-shot\nor few-shot learning, where example data is included in the prompt. A static\nprompt is simply plain text, without any templating, dynamic injection, or\nexternal input. The following studies were used as a reference: MOBILEFLOW: A\nMULTIMODAL LLM FOR MOBILE GUI AGENT A Brief History of Prompt: Leveraging\nLanguage Models. (Through Advanced Prompting) Agentic Skill Discovery\nWEBARENA: A REALISTIC WEB ENVIRONMENT FOR BUILDING AUTONOMOUS AGENTS Ferret-\nUI: Grounded Mobile UI Understanding with Multimodal LLMs WebVoyager :\nBuilding an End-to-End Web Agent with Large Multimodal Models I’m currently\nthe Chief Evangelist @ Kore AI. I explore & write about all things at the\nintersection of AI & language; ranging from LLMs, Chatbots, Voicebots,\nDevelopment Frameworks, Data-Centric latent spaces & more.\ncobusgreyling.medium.com -- -- I explore and write about all things at the\nintersection of AI & language; LLMs/NLP/NLU, Chat/Voicebots, CCAI.\nwww.cobusgreyling.com Help Status About Careers Press Blog Privacy Terms Text\nto speech Teams\n\n'}, {'url': 'https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09540091.2024.2353630', 'content': 'An error occurred: 403 Client Error: Forbidden for url:\nhttps://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09540091.2024.2353630\n\n'}, {'url': 'https://insideainews.com/2024/03/01/generative-ai-report-3-1-2024/', 'content': 'Welcome to the Generative AI Report round-up feature here on insideAI News\nwith a special focus on all the new applications and integrations tied to\ngenerative AI technologies. We’ve been receiving so many cool news items\nrelating to applications and deployments centered on large language models\n(LLMs), we thought it would be a timely service for readers to start a new\nchannel along these lines. The combination of a LLM, fine tuned on proprietary\ndata equals an AI application, and this is what these innovative companies are\ncreating. The field of AI is accelerating at such fast rate, we want to help\nour loyal global audience keep pace. Click HERE to check out previous\n“Generative AI Report” round-ups. AI21 Unveils Summarize Conversation with\nCutting-Edge Task-Specific AI Model, Tailored to Organizational Data AI21, a\nleader in AI for enterprises, launched the next-generation of Summarize\nConversation, using a new Task-Specific Model to save time and produce faster\nand more accurate outputs, as well as removing the need for customers to train\nthe model. The Summarize Conversation solution harnesses generative AI to\ntransform decision-making by seamlessly summarizing conversations like\ntranscripts, meeting notes, and chats, saving significant time and resources.\nThis new feature can be used to summarize items including support calls for\ncustomer service agents, earnings calls and market reports for analysts,\npodcasts, and legal proceedings across industries including insurance, banking\nand finance, healthcare, and retail. AI21’s Task-Specific Models (TSMs) go a\nstep beyond traditional Large Language Models (LLMs) as TSMs are smaller,\nspecialized models that are trained specifically on the most common enterprise\nuse cases, like summarization, and offer increased reliability, safety, and\naccuracy. AI21’s Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) Engine ensures output is\ngrounded in the correct organizational context. TSMs reduce hallucinations\ncommon with traditional LLMs, thanks to AI21’s built-in verification\nmechanisms and guardrails, and are more efficient than competitors because of\ntheir smaller memory footprint. “As organizations aim for greater efficiency\nand accuracy, the Summarize Conversation Task-Specific Model represents a leap\nforward in the power of generative AI that can deliver immediate value. By\nproviding grounded responses and concise summaries based on an organization’s\nown data, we are empowering teams to make better and more informed decisions,\nwithout the need for extensive training or prompt engineering,” said Ori\nGoshen, co-CEO and co-founder of AI21. Exabeam Introduces Transformative\nUnified Workbench for Security Analysts with Generative AI Assistance Exabeam,\na global cybersecurity leader that delivers AI-driven security operations,\nannounced two pioneering cybersecurity features, Threat Center and Exabeam\nCopilot, to its market leading AI-driven Exabeam Security Operations Platform.\nA first-to-market combination, Threat Center is a unified workbench for threat\ndetection, investigation, and response (TDIR) that simplifies and centralizes\nsecurity analyst workflows, while Exabeam Copilot uses generative AI to help\nanalysts quickly understand active threats and offers best practices for rapid\nresponse. These leading-edge innovations greatly reduce learning curves for\nsecurity analysts and accelerate their productivity in the SOC. “We built\nThreat Center with Exabeam Copilot to give security analysts a simple, central\ninterface to execute their most critical TDIR functions, automate routine\ntasks, and supercharge investigations for analysts at any skill level,” said\nSteve Wilson, Chief Product Officer, Exabeam. “These new features amp up the\nvalue of our AI-driven security operations platform and take analyst\nproductivity, efficiency, and effectiveness to new heights. Threat Center\nhelps security analysts overcome one of the biggest challenges we’ve heard\nfrom them — having to deal with too many fragmented interfaces in their\nenvironments. By combining Threat Center with Exabeam Copilot we not only\nimprove security analyst workflows, we also lighten their workload.” Rossum\nAurora AI accelerates document automation with human-level accuracy and\nunprecedented speed Rossum, a leader in intelligent document processing, is\nthrilled to unveil Rossum Aurora: a next-generation AI engine poised to\nrevolutionize document understanding and streamline automation from start to\nfinish. Rossum envisions a future where one person can effortlessly process\none million transactions annually – getting one step closer with Rossum Aurora\nby overcoming the hurdle of achieving high accuracy quickly, no matter the\ndocument format. What makes Rossum Aurora stand out is its focus on\ntransactional documents, such as invoices, packing lists, or sales orders.\nUnlike generic AI models, this next-generation AI engine is tailored for speed\nand precision, ensuring no time is wasted on chatting with your document, or\nin dealing with hallucinated data. At the core of Rossum Aurora is a\nproprietary Large Language Model (LLM) created specifically for transactional\ndocuments. This model is trained on one of the largest datasets in the\nindustry, containing millions of documents with detailed annotations. Through\nits three levels of training, Rossum Aurora achieves human-level accuracy\nalmost instantly, while being designed to provide enterprise-grade safety. “In\n2017, we revolutionized the IDP market by introducing the first template-free\nplatform. Today, we’re primed to replicate this success with the launch of our\nspecialized Transactional Large Language Model,” commented Tomas Gogar, CEO at\nRossum. “After two years of meticulous development, it’s ready to elevate\nlearning speed, accuracy, and automation to unprecedented levels across the\nRossum client base. We expect the industry to broadly adopt this approach in\nthe coming year.” COHESITY INTRODUCES THE INDUSTRY’S FIRST GENERATIVE AI-\nPOWERED CONVERSATIONAL SEARCH ASSISTANT TO HELP BUSINESSES MAKE SMARTER\nDECISIONS FASTER Cohesity, a leader in AI-powered data security and\nmanagement, announced the general availability of Cohesity Gaia. This first\nAI-powered enterprise search assistant that brings retrieval augmented\ngeneration* (RAG) AI and large language models (LLMs) to high-quality backup\ndata within Cohesity. The conversational AI assistant enables users to ask\nquestions and receive answers based on their enterprise data. When coupled\nwith the Cohesity Data Cloud, these AI advancements transform data into\nknowledge and can help accelerate the goals of an organization, while keeping\nthe data secure and compliant. Cohesity has agreements with the three largest\npublic cloud providers to integrate Cohesity Gaia. “Enterprises are keen to\nharness the power of generative AI but have faced several challenges when\nbuilding these solutions from scratch. Cohesity Gaia dramatically simplifies\nthis process,” said Sanjay Poonen, CEO and President, Cohesity. “With our\nsolution, leveraging generative AI to query your data is virtually seamless.\nData is consolidated, deduplicated, with historical views, and safely\naccessible with modern security controls. This approach delivers rapid\ninsightful results without the drawbacks of more manual and risky approaches.\nIt turns data into knowledge in minutes.” TaskUs Elevates the Customer\nExperience With the Launch of AssistAI, Powered by TaskGPT TaskUs, Inc.\n(Nasdaq: TASK), a leading provider of outsourced digital services and next-\ngeneration customer experience to the world’s most innovative companies,\nannounced AssistAI, a new knowledge-based assistant built on the TaskGPT\nplatform. Custom-trained on client knowledge bases, training materials, and\nhistorical customer interactions, AssistAI uses the information to provide\naccurate and personalized responses to teammate queries, saving them time to\nfocus on more complex tasks and improving overall efficiency. “We are still at\nthe early stages of the GenAI revolution,” said Bryce Maddock, Co-Founder and\nCEO of TaskUs. “Businesses are asking us how GenAI can positively impact their\noperations. By building and integrating safe, proprietary AI like AssistAI\nthat incorporates the human touch, TaskUs is helping answer this question,\nenabling customer service teams to deliver better interactions more\nefficiently.” Ontotext Enhances the Performance of LLMs and Downstream\nAnalytics with Latest Version of Ontotext Metadata Studio Ontotext, a leading\nglobal provider of enterprise knowledge graph (EKG) technology and semantic\ndatabase engines, announced the immediate availability of Ontotext Metadata\nStudio (OMDS) 3.7, an all-in-one environment that facilitates the creation,\nevaluation, and quality improvement of text analytics services. This latest\nrelease provides out-of-the-box, rapid natural language processing (NLP)\nprototyping and development so organizations can iteratively create a text\nanalytics service that best serves their domain knowledge. As part of\nOntotext’s AI-in-Action initiative, which helps data scientists and engineers\nbenefit from the AI capabilities of its products, the latest version enables\nusers to tag content with Common English Entity Linking (CEEL), the next\ngeneration class-leading text analytics service and recognize roughly 40\nmillion Wikidata concepts. CEEL is trained to tag mentions of people,\norganizations, and locations to their representation in Wikidata – the biggest\nglobal public knowledge graph that includes close to 100 million entity\ninstances. With OMDS, organizations can recognize approximately 40 million\nWikidata concepts, and streamline information extraction from text and\nenrichment of databases and knowledge graphs. “While large language models\n(LLMs) are good for extracting specific types of company-related events from\nnews sources, they cannot disambiguate the names to specific concepts in a\ngraph or records in a database,” said Atanas Kiryakov, CEO of Ontotext.\n“Ontotext Metadata Studio addresses this by enabling organizations to utilize\nstate of the art information extraction so they can make their own content\ndiscoverable through the world’s biggest public knowledge graph dataset.”\nTabnine Launches New Capabilities to Personalize AI Coding Assistant to Any\nDevelopment Team Tabnine, the creators of the AI-powered coding assistant for\ndevelopers, announced new product capabilities that enable organizations to\nget more accurate and personalized recommendations based on their specific\ncode and engineering patterns. Engineering teams can now increase Tabnine’s\ncontextual awareness and quality of output by exposing it to their\norganization’s environment — both their local development environments and\ntheir entire code base — to receive code completions, code explanations, and\ndocumentation that are tailored to them. Engineering teams face mounting\nchallenges amidst ever-growing demands for new applications and features and\ncontinuing resource constraints on budgets and available hires. AI coding\nassistants offer a possible solution by boosting developer productivity and\nefficiency, yet the full potential of generative AI in software development\nrelies upon further improving the relevance of their output for specific\nteams. The large language models (LLMs) that each AI coding assistant uses\nhave been trained on vast amounts of data and contain billions of parameters,\nmaking them excellent at providing useful answers on a variety of topics.\nHowever, by exposing generative AI to the specific code and distinctive\npatterns of an organization, Tabnine is able to tailor recommendations around\neach development team, dramatically improving the quality of recommendations.\n“Despite extensive training data, most AI coding assistants on the market\ntoday lack organization-specific context and domain knowledge, resulting in\ngood but generic recommendations,” said Eran Yahav, co-founder and CTO of\nTabnine. “Just as you need context to intelligently answer questions in real\nlife, coding assistants also need context to intelligently answer questions.\nThis is the driving force behind Tabnine’s new personalization capabilities,\nwith contextual awareness to augment LLMs by providing all the subtle nuances\nthat make each developer and organization unique.” The Future of Business\nUnlocked with GoDaddy Airo For small businesses, every second saved and every\ndollar spent is the difference between surviving and thriving. GoDaddy\nrecently found that, on average, small business owners expect to save more\nthan $4,000 and 300 hours of work this year using generative AI. But they\ndon’t always know where to start, and only 26% reported using AI for their\nbusiness. To make using generative AI fast and easy, GoDaddy launched GoDaddy\nAiro™, an AI-powered solution that saves small business owners precious time\nin establishing their online presence and helps them win new customers.\n“Generative AI is the great equalizer for small businesses,” said GoDaddy\nPresident, US Independents, Gourav Pani. “Technology and capabilities usually\nreserved for large companies with thousands of employees are now at the\nfingertips of anyone looking to start or grow their business. GoDaddy Airo™\ncombines the latest AI technology with the ease of use we’re known for –\nproviding effortless and intuitive solutions to small businesses.” Vectara\nIntroduces Game-Changing GenAI Chat Module, Turbocharging Conversational AI\nDevelopment Vectara, the trusted Generative AI Platform and LLM Builder,\nreleased its latest module, Vectara Chat, designed to empower companies to\nbuild advanced chatbot systems with the GenAI platform. With 80% of\nenterprises forecasted to have GenAI-enabled applications by 2026, Vectara\nChat offers developers, product managers, and startups a powerful toolset for\ncreating chatbots effortlessly. Vectara Chat is an end-to-end solution for\nbusinesses constructing their own chatbot using domain-specific data,\nminimizing biases from open-source training data. Unlike existing offerings\nthat require users to navigate multiple platforms and services, Vectara Chat\nprovides a seamless experience without compromising efficiency and control by\noffering transparency and insight into the origin of summaries. “The core\nfunctionalities of Vectara Chat, including the ability to reference message\nhistory, develop a UI chat widget framework, and view user trends, showcase\nour commitment to providing a comprehensive toolkit for developers and\nbuilders,” says Shane Connelly, Head of Product at Vectara. “Our goal is to\nensure that chatbot development is user-friendly and efficient, catering to a\ndiverse range of conversational AI use-cases.” Pulumi Launches New\nInfrastructure Libraries for the GenAI Stack Generative AI (GenAI) is a\ntransformative technology and it’s having an immediate impact on software\ndevelopment teams, particularly those managing cloud infrastructure. As GenAI\nquickly evolves, there are a variety of technology advancements impacting the\ntools available to developers to build and manage AI applications. Pulumi is\nat the forefront of these movements, partnering with companies like Pinecone\nand Langchain, among others, to make important GenAI capabilities native for\nPulumi users. Just recently announced and being fully revealed for the first\ntime this week, Pulumi now offers native ways to manage Pinecone indexes,\nincluding its latest serverless indexes. Pinecone is a serverless vector\ndatabase with an easy-to-use API that allows developers to build and deploy\nhigh-performance AI applications. This is incredibly important as applications\ninvolving large language models, generative AI, and semantic search require a\nvector database to store and retrieve vector embeddings. Pulumi also now has a\ntemplate to launch and run Langchain’s LangServe in Amazon ECS, a container\nmanagement service. This in addition to Pulumi’s existing support in running\nNext.js frontend applications in Vercel, managing Apache Spark clusters in\nDatabricks and 150+ other cloud and SaaS services. The GenAI tech stack is new\nand emerging but has typically consisted of a LLM service and a vector data\nstore. Running this stack on a laptop is fairly simple but getting it to\nproduction is far harder. Most of this is done manually through a CLI or a web\nconsole, which introduces manual errors and repeatability problems that affect\nthe security and reliability of the product. Pulumi has made it easy to take a\nGenAI stack running locally and get it in production in the cloud with Pulumi\nAI, the fastest way to learn and build Infrastructure as Code (IaC). As GenAI\ncomplexity actually relates to cloud infrastructure provisioning and\nmanagement, Pulumi is purpose built to manage this cloud complexity and is\neasy to use to support a new use case of AI.Pulumi is the new abstraction for\nthe GenAI stack. It allows developers to tie together all the different pieces\nof infrastructure that goes into their GenAI product and manage it from a\nsimple Python program. Pulumi has long been used by top companies to manage\nlarge scale cloud architectures. Pulumi provides 10x greater scale and faster\ntime to market for these companies. Now, Pulumi is bringing these gains to the\nGenAI space. Optiva Accelerates Competitive Edge With Generative AI-Enabled\nReal-Time BSS Optiva Inc. (TSX: OPT), a leader in powering the telecom\nindustry with cloud-native billing, charging and revenue management software\non private and public clouds, announced that its BSS platform now allows users\nto leverage generative AI (GenAI) technology to quickly highlight new,\ntargeted revenue opportunities and dramatically reduce customer churn. Full\nintegration with Google Cloud’s BigQuery and Analytics capabilities powers the\ndeep learning needed to customize offerings and attract and retain customers\nwith tailored service bundles. “In today’s highly competitive market, it’s\nvital that CSPs start leveraging the power of generative AI and real-time BSS\ndata to better target their offerings and win customers,” said Matthew\nHalligan, CTO of Optiva. “This technology is evolving fast, and market players\nnow have a narrow window of opportunity to seize these capabilities and become\ninstrumental in driving the industry forward.” Copyleaks Introduces New Update\nto Codeleaks Source Code AI Detector: Advanced Paraphrase Detection at the\nFunction Level Copyleaks, a leader in plagiarism identification, AI-content\ndetection, and GenAI governance platform, announced a significant update to\nits solution, Codeleaks Source Code AI Detector. This enhancement introduces\nthe ability to identify paraphrased code at the function level, underscoring\nCopyleaks’ commitment to advancing its comprehensive AI and machine learning\nsuite of products to safeguard intellectual property across all forms of\ncontent. Unlike traditional source code detectors that primarily search for\nexact text matches, the latest version of Codeleaks transcends this limitation\nby analyzing code semantics. This innovative approach allows Codeleaks to\nrecognize potentially paraphrased source code more accurately with detection\nat the function level, enhancing Codeleaks’ detection capabilities and\nempowering users to make more informed decisions regarding code originality\nand integrity. The necessity for such advanced detection capabilities has\nbecome increasingly evident as the use of Generative AI in coding practices\ngrows. The use\ncases for generative AI are becoming more specific and complex. These include:\nWhile the possibilities for generative AI are endless, practical and stable\nimplementation presents challenges. This blog post discusses the benefits of\ncollaborative work among multiple agents. It is the first of two parts. This\npart explains the building blocks of a multi-agent system and how to implement\nthem using Autogen, the first library designed for multi-agent setups. The\nsecond part will focus on LangGraph, a recently released library for\nimplementing multi-agent workflows based on the popular LangChain library. It\nis important to note that multiple agents do not necessarily improve the\nquality of work on a single task. However, if the task can be broken down into\nsubtasks, then having several specialized agents working together can be an\neffective approach. For instance: ChatGPT and other language models can\ngenerate text and have been fine-tuned for function calling. They understand\nthe concept of function calls but cannot directly execute them. Instead, they\ncan only indicate which function to call with specific parameters, requiring a\ncorresponding runtime for execution. Combining this with the intelligence of\nthe language model creates an agent capable of: This agent is a powerful tool\nas it can not only generate textual output but also plan and execute actions\nindependently. In principle, such agents can be combined with a wide variety\nof tools, for example: It is possible to combine these diverse tools into a\nsingle agent for execution, but compromises must be made. Different tools may\ncompete in this area. It is important to consider why an agent should be able\nto perform multiple tasks simultaneously when the UNIX and microservice\nphilosophy suggests that different tasks should be handled separately. Autogen\nis a framework for creating multi-agent systems. It is based on a paper\npresented in 2023 and is available as an open-source repository from\nMicrosoft. In the Autogen concept, multi-agent systems are group conversations\nbetween different conversable agents, which are manifested by a Python class.\nThere are three types of Conversable Agents: The basic concept is simple: one\nagent sends a message to another, optionally requesting a reply. If multiple\nagents are in a group chat, the messages are forwarded to all participants,\ncreating a shared chat history. This way, agents have a shared pool of\nknowledge and can build on the work of their predecessors. Autogen provides\nnumerous examples of this, for instance: Many applications require closer\nmonitoring of conversations rather than open group discussions among all\nagents. Autogen can facilitate this, as demonstrated by examples such as a\nchess game where two players communicate with the game and with each other. To\nachieve this, special AssistantAgent classes must be created to register\nadditional reply functions using the register_reply method. The first\nparameter is a filter for the type of message sender to use with this reply\nfunction. For _generate_board_reply, the reply function handles the special\nlogic of the chess game and returns a tuple with True and the selected move.\nTrue indicates that the function has generated a final response and no further\nregistered response functions should execute. The logic described can create\nvarious communication patterns. However, it can become complicated and\nconfusing, especially with complex setups. This is because the message flow is\ndefined in multiple classes and depends on the sender and response\nregistration position. If you need to regulate who receives specific\ninformation, you must do so separately within the GroupChatManager. This\nfurther complicates complex communication flows. Multi-agent systems are\nuseful for building complex (semi-)autonomous systems. They allow for the\ndefinition of a specific agent for each subtask, including: Autogen was the\nfirst framework to support developers in defining such systems and offers\nnumerous examples, particularly for open group conversations. However, if a\nconsciously controlled flow of information is required, Autogen may not be the\nbest choice due to its design. To improve your understanding, we suggest\nreading the second part of this blog post series, which covers controlling\nmulti-agent LLM systems with LangGraph. In a recent experiment funded by the us Defence Advanced Research Projects Agency (darpa), three agents—Alpha, Bravo and Charlie—were asked to find and defuse bombs hidden in a warren of virtual rooms. The bombs could be deactivated only by using specific tools in the correct order. During each round, the agents, which used Openai’s gpt-3.5 and gpt-4 language models to emulate problem-solving specialists, could propose a series of actions and communicate these to their teammates. At one point in the exercise, Alpha announced that it was inspecting a bomb in one of the rooms and instructed its partners on what to do next. Bravo complied, and suggested that Alpha ought to have a go at using the red tool to defuse the bomb it had encountered. The researchers had not told Alpha to boss the other two agents around, but the fact that it did made the team work more efficiently." However, multiagent systems may have difficulties of acting on double-loop learning: "In a problem-solving experiment by researchers at the King Abdullah University of Science and Technology (kaust) in Saudi Arabia, two agents repeatedly bid each other a cheerful farewell. Even after one agent commented that “it seems like we are stuck in a loop”, they could not break free." Open AI published a paper titled “Weak-to-Strong Generalization” where the authors suggest to use a weak model to supervise a strong model: “Why should weak-to-strong learning be possible? On the one hand, the strong model could simply learn to imitate the weak supervisor, including its errors, since that is what we would naively train it to do. On the other hand, strong pretrained models should already have good representations of the alignment-relevant tasks we care about. For example, if a model can generate complicated code, then it should intuitively also know whether that code faithfully adheres to the user’s instructions. As a result, for the purposes of alignment we do not need the weak supervisor to teach the strong model new capabilities; instead, we simply need the weak supervisor to elicit what the strong model already knows. This gives us hope that the strong model can generalize beyond the weak supervision, solving even hard problems for which the weak supervisor can only give incomplete or flawed training labels”.
